sql:
SELECT model_type
FROM survival_models
WHERE model_type = 'Kaplan-Meier';

external_knowledge:
- Survival analysis is a branch of statistics that deals with the analysis of time-to-event data; 
- Hazard rates represent the rate of events (e.g., failures, deaths) occurring at a specific time, given that the individual has survived up to that time;
- Covariates are variables that are associated with the probability of an event (e.g., age, sex, treatment group);
- Model coefficients for covariates represent the change in the hazard rate for a one-unit change in the covariate, assuming all other covariates are held constant;
- AIC (Akaike information criterion) and BIC (Bayesian information criterion) are metrics used for model selection, with lower values indicating a better fit;
- Log-likelihood is a measure of the model's goodness of fit, with higher values indicating a better fit.

